{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658115"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.88,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95135"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78103"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11712"},{"type":"tags","id":"12587"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32659"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95135"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a three-day history of fever, right lower quadrant abdominal pain, and anorexia. Laboratory tests show an elevated white blood cell count of 15 \u00d7 10^9/L (4-11). Laparoscopy reveals an inflamed appendix with surrounding purulent exudate. The appendix is surgically removed, and the patient recovers without complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the potential outcome of acute inflammation if left untreated in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spontaneous tissue necrosis with calcification","Transformation into granulomatous inflammation","Formation of an abscess","Complete resolution with full tissue regeneration","Immediate progression to fibrosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely outcome of untreated acute appendicitis would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of an abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. Abscesses develop when the acute inflammatory process is unable to eliminate the inciting agent (in this case, likely bacterial infection causing appendicitis). The accumulation of neutrophils, tissue debris, and fluid creates a confined pocket of pus that becomes walled off by fibrinous exudate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other potential outcomes are less likely in this scenario:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete resolution with full tissue regeneration\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely without removal of the inciting stimulus and with ongoing bacterial proliferation in appendicitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate progression to fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs after the acute phase has subsided and when there is substantial tissue destruction or abundant fibrin exudation, but is not the immediate outcome of untreated appendicitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransformation into granulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of specific pathogens like mycobacteria or fungi, not the typical bacteria causing appendicitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpontaneous tissue necrosis with calcification\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical immediate outcome of acute inflammation; calcification may occur in chronic conditions over a longer period\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe four main outcomes of acute inflammation are: (1) complete resolution with restoration of normal tissue architecture, (2) abscess formation, (3) progression to chronic inflammation, and (4) fibrosis. In appendicitis, without treatment, the inflammatory process typically leads to abscess formation, perforation, or peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute inflammation can resolve completely, progress to chronic inflammation, form an abscess, or lead to fibrosis depending on the nature and extent of the injury.","Untreated appendicitis typically progresses to abscess formation, perforation, or peritonitis.","Abscess formation occurs when neutrophils, tissue debris, and fluid create a confined pocket of pus walled off by fibrinous exudate."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78103"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78103"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T11:05:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T11:06:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95135"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:3